name: Juwel Aquarium Primo 60 / AniOne Aquarium Starter Kit 60 - Futterring / Futterblende / Futtereinsatz
description:
Passend für:

- Juwel Primo 60
- AniOne Aquarium Starter Kit 60 (von Fressnapf) 

Wenn man keinen Futter-Ring hat oder auch keine Lust hat immer zu versuchen diesen durch die Luke zu treffen, dann ist das hier die richtige und einfachste Lösung. Hiermit geht nichts daneben und bleibt wo es sein soll. Wenn der Ring (das Endstück) nicht mehr im Wasser ist, ist auch nicht mehr genug Wasser im Aquarium. Das Endstück reicht ca. 5-6 mm ins Wasser. Die kleine Blende lässt sich nach links und nach rechts verschieben oder auch ganz einfach rausnehmen um diese z.B. zu säubern. Unbeabsichtigtes Reinfallen der Futterhilfe schließe ich aus. Wenn man es nicht absichtlich falsch macht, bleibt die Blende wo sie soll. 

PLA sollte für diesen Zweck hier unbedenklich sein. Wer sicher gehen will druckt vielleicht lebensmittelecht in PETG.

Viel Spaß damit! 

PS: Wer mag, kann sich gerne mit einer kleinen Spende bedanken.

name: Jebao DCS-1200 intake cover for Red Sea Max Nano
description:
Jebao (or Jecod) DSC-1200 pump is great replacement for Sicce pump provided by Red Sea. Its cheaper to buy it in case if stock one fails and its a 24V DC pump with variable speed controller which is an added benefit.

It is a bit bigger than the stock one and although it fits its performance is slightly limited because intake is too close to side glass panel of the tank. To fix it I've designed this intake cover which makes the pump sit nice an tight between two glass panels wit maximal available clearance from the intake allowing best water flow.

I tested it in my tank and water level in pump compartment dropped by few centimeters :)

One more issue you'd have to fix yourself is to remove back cover from the pump and make a small notch to fit the cable as close to the pump as possible, I used a round file, sharp knife should also do. You can also use a hacksaw to remove part of the intake thread it should also improve the flow a bit.

Cover is a remix of intake cover that comes with the pump, but its shorted and has open end. It fits the same adapter, but if you lost yours worry not, I got you covered (pun intended) ;)

name: Formicarium for very new colonies - Replace water without moving the queen
description:
This splitter for formicarium allows small colonies, still in vials, to stay in their original container when you need to replace the water. 

I've wanted to avoid stress on early colonies when replacing water, and since I haven't found anything I liked, I made it myself. I will continue to do tweaks as time passes. 

Connexions are for the Nest, Water tube, and Foraging area. I feed the ants in the foraging area, so the nest is mainly untouched. Place a cotton ball in the hole without tube to allow air through. When you need to move the colony to a bigger nest, just place the adapter with a tube, and open the lid of the nest.

Printed with 10% supports, remove them with a little drill slowly. The nest box hole will probably need a bit of sanding, as it's very tight (So light can't get through). Beware, clear colour filaments will allow light through, so if you decide to print it in white or other bright colours, paint the insides black, so it doesn't bother the ants.

Any tips to improve the build is welcome. Feel free to distribute and modify any files.

name: Wheelie dog sign
description: This object is a simple 3D-printable wheelie dog sign suitable for attaching to a stroller or wheelchair or whatever you like! Owners of dogs with spine or rear leg troubles know the funny looks they get as they cart their dogs around in a stroller. After a year we decided to make it easier on everyone and just print a little wheelchair sign to indicate that the dog is disabled. But why use a human one? This simple model started as a 2D silhouette of a french bulldog, modified in MS Paint of all things and then converted to SVG, imported into Fusion 360, and extruded and slightly manipulated there. The model has some connecting material between the dog and wheelchair - fill it in with black ink for a better look. There are three small pegs on the back, we pushed these through the mesh of the stroller and attached some Sugru to hold in place.

name: Piramide Mascota orgonica base 600x600
description:
Pirámide con piezas huecas para ser rellenada por material orgónico que puede utilizarse como cama para las mascotas si se coloca algo blando en su parte central.
NO NECESITA SOPORTES.
Las piezas Superior e Inferiores están diseñadas para ser impresas en 3D, con tubos de unión diámetro 50mm de los que se usan para fontanería.
La pirámide se debe completar con relleno de material orgónico en todas las piezas.
El material orgónico consta de virutas de aluminio y arena de cuarzo con resina (poliamida o epoxi), todo mezclado al 33,33% de volumen.
Todas las piezas deben ir rellenas de material orgónico.
Antes de realizar el relleno se deben pegar las piezas con pegamento para tubos de fontanería (pegamento para PVC). Para mejorar la estabilidad se pueden fijar también con los tirantes que aconsejo sean de cable de aluminio.
El relleno debe realizarse de abajo hacia arriba.
Adicionalmente el proyecto tiene cables para estabilización y toma de tierra. (ver proyecto en 3D)
Se puede variar el tamaño de la pirámide cambiando el tamaño de las barras de pvc.
Los soportes de los tubos horizontales en la pieza EngancheInferior.stl se sacan estirando con el tornillo impreso: TornilloJ3DM16x80.stl

name: Small Airtag Collar Strap
description:

Must be printed in a flexible filament, I used TPU. Keep the infill as low as possible for more flex on the strap. I printed it at 5% infill with the rounded side down and supports on the build plate.

name: Dog Business widget
description:
I needed something to identify whether the dog has been feed or taken outside to do his business, because we all leave at different times for work.  This is a device which spins and lets you inform other people in the house instead of leaving a paper note.  

All you need is two 608RS bearings.  This was what I had leftover from a previous project.  

You will need to split the model into parts, and print each individual component separately.  No supports required.   I made the spinner shaft longer than necessary, but they are easily trimmed with scissors or a dremel to the desired length.

To assemble:
1. fit the bearings over the posts on the base
2. put the spinners onto the bearings
3. place the lid over the spinners, test fit the knobs, and trim spinner shaft if desired
4. use small amounts of cyanoacrylate glue to secure the lid to the base (make sure the spinners are inside first)
5. attach the knobs

I printed mine in PETG, so it may be necessary to adjust sizes to account for different expansions.  I add 0.15mm X/Y expansion to go from PLA to PETG.  YMMV

name: Bracket for dual terrarium hood setup for perfect bearded dragon lighting
description:
I wanted the perfect lighting setup for our bearded dragon's 40 gallon Zoo Med terrarium that we purchased from PetSmart. Unfortunately, they only have the dome lamps that only cover one third of the terrarium's total length. We wanted a lighting setup that provided both heat and UV-A/B lighting across the entire back of the tank. 

I finally decided to get two 18" dual Naturalistic lamps from Zoo Med. They are not designed to fit a 40 gallon tank which measures 36" inches in length, though they almost fit almost perfectly on top. Each lamp has a socket for both ONE heat lamp and ONE UV lamp. On the left I put a RED night lamp and on the right I put a BLUE daylight heat lamp. I noticed there is a gap in between, and if I only had a bracket that the lamps could snap into, it would not only support the two lamps and keep them from buckling into the screen mesh, but it would also help keep them centered and aligned with the edges of the tank, so as long as you secure the bracket centered with two-sided tape.

I don't know the exact volume of the scoop, I just made an educated guess on how much I need for my two gerbils.

name: Small Pet Feeder - once a day
description:
My daughter needed a pet feeder for her hedgehogs while we go on vacation.  I started by trying out a few auger-type pet feeders but they always would bind on the food and stop.  There was a few that were creative and wiggled the motor to try to keep it from binding but I always had trouble with it.  So, I made this monstrosity.  It's sort of ugly and I don't know if my daughter will even like it or use it but I thought I'd post it on here in case it was just what someone was looking for.  I'll admit, it's sort of weird so I sort of doubt my daughter will like it, but I had fun making it.  Anyway, I hope one of you out there like it.

It drops pet kibble once a day from the buckets.  It uses an arduino mega, a 1602 lcd with buttons, a 5v stepper motor, and an led.  I should have probably used an arduino uno or nano but I had a few arduino megas already, so I used that.

I made the chain link first as I wanted it to be able to print without supports and then made it with the smaller bucket but the wife thought it wasn't big enough so I made the bigger bucket.  I included a tank tred link for fun so I suppose the chain links could be used for a lot of projects.  Most of the pieces don't need supports but some of them like the cog and brace do.  The cog with the motor, you'll want to superglue the axel to the cog (but don't superglue it to the standard).  The other cog, you'll want to leave free wheeling but you may want to superglue that axel to the standard.  You can feed the chain through and then connect it after it's put together.

I've included the arduino sketch if you want to program an arduino mega and build one.

The idea is that this thing will sit on top of the hedgehog cage and drop the food down onto a plate.  I suppose this could work for sitting above a fishtank also.

If you opt to not print buckets all the way around and use some plain old chain links, you should make sure you at least balance the same number of buckets on both sides of the chain otherwise it makes it really hard for the weak 5v stepper to turn the whole chain. Also, don't make the brace too tight or else the chain won't turn - there needs to be a little slack, but not too much.

Here's a video of it:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n_U--DCuswk

name: 3D Printed Parts for DIY Chicken Coop Automated Door

This projects is fully described here (all mechanical parts, electronics and software) : https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NRBMtOAgGudBAg5cqmmfRA5f5Oi3NSKeDBwCM5mq0wo/edit?usp=sharing

Key characteristics :
- It relies on light level to automaticaly open and close the door
- it uses most easy to find, cheap and reliable components (nodemcu ESP8266, 28BYJ-48 stepper motor, ULN2003 driver board, Si7021, simple LDR and basic resistor)
- There is also a temperature and humidity monitoring
- The system is connected through wifi, sharing all its data and allowing Over The Air setup
- It is powered through usb cable (5V)

name: Dog Leash Handle
description:
Dog people told me to use inexpensive paracord as a leash for walking and running my dog.  This thinner rope gives incentive for my demonic beast to not rip my shoulder out of socket.  The thin rope also gives me incentive to go to the hospital to glue my fingers back on.  This is my particular solution.

Here's a first draft that I've been using daily for six months with no major issues.  The handle is plenty strong and solves about 99% of the pain problem.  My Lab/German Sheppard could pull down an Apache helicopter.....somehow.  Only the extreme outlier dogs will break this.  

Downsides
In the summer, it gets a little sweaty.  Maybe in the future, I'll add some kind of thermal management.

name: Dog Poo Bag Holder
description:
A holder for a roll of dog poo bags (both 16 and 20 bags).  My intention: there's nothing worse than having to deal with a heavy, lumpy projectile on the leash in a tense moment (sniffing another dog, chasing a squirrel, etc), so I've tried to minimize its weight and size

One uses zipties to fasten it to the leash and the other has hoops for passing the leash through; I made it tight on the leash to keep it from sliding around, so it might be snug.  I've also sized the hole in the lid to fit a 1/4" shaft (75mm / 3" long) to help center the roll, but its not necessary

The bag is a little hard to poke out of the dispensing slot, which also makes it hard to fully unravel / sneak back in

I'm using an Ender 3 and a Monoprice Mini Delta.  I don't like generic supports, so I've added my own and havent had any difficulty removing them / issues with parts printing correctly

Let me know if you need anything else!  Feel free to toss me a tip if you appreciate the work
Thanks!

name: Bottle Holder for Bin Cages
description:
So, I make all of my mice's habitats myself using bins. The bin cages are great but the one huge headache with them is attaching a water bottle. With the lip around the lid, it's hard to get the bottles to sit at the correct angle for the critters to easily get a drink. 

This is a really simple device to attach to the side of the cage. It holds the bottle out away from the lip so it stands upright, which is how to get the water to flow into the tip of the nozzle. The nozzle itself goes through a hole in the bin. 

I hope I got the measurements right! Basically all I need to do is drill holes corresponding to the holes in the base and attach the device (you could use bolts but I'm just gonna use pipe cleaners, it's easier and cheaper). Then the bottle can slide into the ring. I'll update this when I get the printer and make one, and let you know if it works! If you make one I hope you show me. :) Depending on the size of your bottle you might have to adjust the diameter of the ring.

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/8NkEDX63xAx

name: Reef Delete Easy Arm Holder
description:
Reef Delete Easy Arm 

Additional parts required:
1x Acrylic Rod 6mm (available on eBay, craft stores + some LFS as coral pointers) choose length yourself - buy spares incase of assembly/cutting errors

1x Acrylic Rod 10mm (available on eBay, craft stores + some LFS as coral pointers) choose total length yourself - buy spares incase of assembly/cutting errors

1x Nut+Bolt M4 x 30MM - ideally nylon - but stainless or titanium will work.
Small rubber band or O ring

Super glue - for gluing 10mm rod only.

Tools: 4mm, 6mm and 10mm drill bits + drill
Sand paper
Sharp Jnr. Hacksaw for trimming rod - or Dremel with cutting disc (easiest)

Print Instructions:

Print all parts - ideally in ABS - we suggest using a raft for the trigger and reef delete body holder to ease of print. Ream out all printed holes as required for the Nut/Bolt/Acrylic Rods in all parts where fitment is not tight. We recommend a wiggling the 6mm drill bit around when reaming to make the 6mm holes slightly oversize to reduce friction. Note some parts can be a tight/loose fit due to tolerances in 3d printing and the printer’s own calibration in XYZ coordinates + acrylic extruded rod can vary in thickness.  It make may the difference between too loose or too tight. Adjust as required with scaling or slight sanding + reaming of holes with a drill.  

Assembly - Refer to the photos on this page

1. Check you have all parts including 2x of the rod supports

2. Insert 6mm rod into rod cam and glue in place, align as per photo and insert into the trigger body first. This should be able to move freely up and down inside. Sand part sides down if required. Push all the way up so you can then insert the trigger handle and insert the bolt through the assembly and do up hang tight. This does not need to be very tight - its just to act as a lever point. 

3. The whole assembly should look like this and the handle move up and down freely, pushing the rod up and down. 

4. Attach elastic band or a suitable O ring to act as a return spring. You don’t want this too strong, otherwise it will still make your hand ache! Check action as per trigger action video on the Reef Delete Official Owners Group - in the files section - it should all move freely and easily and push the rod out when the trigger is pulled. 

5. Using a jar Hacksaw or Dremel - You will need to trim the 10mm acrylic rod down in length, using sand paper to tidy the edges of the cut so that you have several mm of 6mm rod going into the Reef Delete holder. This length of 6mm rod poking into the holder is critical so it can reach the Reef Delete button so keep checking fitment. Adjust as required. 

6. Final assembly and checks.

Unscrew Reef Delete battery tube, insert Reef Delete body into the holder, refit the battery tube and tighten up. Check that the 6mm rod can push the button down and activate the Reef Delete easily. If you need to adjust this - Cut down 10mm rod to get more length on the 6mm rod if required as per part 5

Assemble as per photo 6. Glue the Rod into the supports ensuring they are evenly spaced and into the trigger and holder, evenly spaced with glue ONLY on the 10mm side. The 6mm side should move freely and is to be only glued into the trigger cam.

If using Stainless nut/bolt ensure on the handle and it gets wet, make sure you rinse with freshwater and hand dry after use to avoid rusting.

name: Hamster Wheel Silent No Supports Easy Print
description:
Designed to be almost fully 3d printable without supports (except for horizontal rod). 

A 72mm x 2mm length of metal needs to be used for the axis of the wheel. For this, I cut a piece of clothes-hanger. This allows for the Wheel Frame, thus Wheel, to spin freely with very little friction :) (It is the Wheel Frame that spins on the axis. The metal rod simply press fits into the main support(s).

I designed this to be as simple as possible and seems to assemble well and spin well with silence.

0.2mm tolerances are built into the design, so this can be easily assembled regardless of print quality.

Hope this helps your little fluffy friends.
Happy printing.
Thanks for viewing :)

name: Surface skimmer - remixed for improved adjustment and floatation
description:

I also increased the air cavity volume underneath the top part of the surface skimmer, so that it floats well, so it should be less dependent on how much infill/wall thickness you use.

I printed these both in black PETG, but PLA should work fine.  
Top cap with two layer wall thickness, 3 layers top and bottom and 20% infill.
All other parts 3 wall thickness.

It has a cord hook on one side to ensure that if the cord is pulled it won't topple the lamp, and it has a tab on the opposite side with a small hole in case one wants to ziptie or twist-tie the base down to the terrarium lid.  

So far, bulb heat hasn't caused the base to warm anywhere near it's glassing temperature.

name: Anchor Hocking Fish Lid Riser
description:
My wife and I got a betta fish.  We used our Anchor Hocking dispenser jar with a stainless steel (bought separately) spout.  The spout will allow us to do easier water changes and the water will be good for our plants.  

The only problem is that by putting the lid on the jar, it robs the fish of air it would normally receive without a lid.  Oh, did I mention we have a cat...  This riser (actually a set of 4 risers) combine to make a full circle to sit on top of the lid/ledge, and there are holes for air circulation, and a groove for the original lid to sit.  The part does not come in contact with the water.  There is a sacrificial piece that is added to the model so it can be printed without supports.  Just pop it off at the end.

There are holes for magnets where the pieces meet, and a link below, but they really don't help.  I should have used 2 magnets vertically, or some sort of tongue and groove setup.  Maybe next time.  

At 5% infill, and a standard Prusa profile, each part takes 3 hours to print and four total are needed.

Magnets:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07KZQGWNN/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1

name: Rear Fan Bracket Mod for Biocube 32
description:
This is a bracket to securely hold a 40mm fan on the rear cable opening of a Biocube 32 aquarium. It will provide air current to cool the aquarium and maintain optimal temps.
While most 40mm fans may work, I have only tested (and designed) it to be used with a AC Infinity 40x20mm USB fan found on Amazon.
https://smile.amazon.com/gp/product/B07CNJ4DYX/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_search_asin_title?ie=UTF8&psc=1

I would recommend this fan as well as a Inkbird controller so that the fan will come on automatically. I presume that most fans of this size will fit the bracket. 

1. Print the fan with Support, .3 Layer Height, 2mm Wall thickness and 75% infill. PLA.
2. Obtain longer screws (20mm worked) - You don't have to get them super tight.
3. Move all cable to one of the two Cable Holes on the rear of the Biocube 32
4. Mount fan on Bracket and then place bracket into one of the cable ports on the hood of your biocube 32. It should easily snap into place. Make sure the wording faces UP. This is important because there is a tab on the bottom which rests on the bottom lip of the cable port. Without this tab, the bracket will shift downward and will snap off when the hood is opened.

My tank would overheat every day with the Steve's LEDs lighting system. This bracket will allow the fan to maintain the tank temp to within .5 degrees when combined with a auto-on temp controller like the Inkbird.
comments: Thanks!Thank you for sharing your design. It works like a charm for the Biocube 16 as well (2022 model) - no modifications necessary! I posted it in the Makes.

description:

It is very easy to accidentally press the "empty all litter" button rather than manually cycling the machine so this covers it, making it impossible to press with a finger. Instead, you press the button underneath through the small hole in the guard with a pencil or similar stylus. It should fit loosely enough that it doesn't bind to the button but tightly enough to stay put. 

A STEP version is included to allow for easy customization.

Please note that pressing firmly on the button guard (or anywhere on the control panel for that matter) can trigger the Litter-Robot's weight-based sensor. It can be canceled by pressing the "Reset" button.

name: Equine Tracheostomy Device
description:
THIS PART HAS NOT YET BEEN TESTED, USE AT YOUR OWN RISK, FOR LICENSED VETERINARY USE ONLY.

Credit on the overall design concept belongs to Pape as these are generically called Pape's Model tracheostomy devices. I was unable to locate Pape after an extended search so if anyone knows who they are or how to contact them please comment below.

This part is intended to be disposable and one time use. Do not attempt to sanitize after use. 3D prints absorb fluids and are almost impossible to properly sanitize once used on a patient.


FOLLOW THE FOLLOWING INSTRUCTIONS TO SANITIZE THE DEVICE PRIOR TO USE:

https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32232596/


Please reference the following literature on performing the operation:

http://www.veterinaryirelandjournal.com/large-animal/163-nursing-care-of-equine-tracheostomy-patients

https://vetgirlontherun.com/how-to-perform-an-equine-emergency-tracheostomy-in-the-field-vetgirl-veterinary-continuing-education-blog/

https://www.vetfolio.com/learn/article/permanent-tracheostomy



Now on to this particular device

I added some additional features from the original design:

The large arrow indicates the correct direction of air flow into the lungs.

The center breathing hole features a hex nut to clamp and hold while threading in a 3/4" pipe attachment if an additional tube connection is required.

The two posts with the holes in them are for tying the device together for extra security so it can't slip apart. You can either take surgical thread and wrap it around both posts after tying off to one of the posts and then tie off to the other post when completed several turns as shown in the diagram, or alternatively if you have thicker rope you can just tie knots around both posts until the assembly stops moving.

I don't view that this is the most secure attachment, and I understand the convenience of simple screws and bolts, however I am trying to make manufacturing and using this as simple as possible for folks in third world countries who may not have access to specific metric screw sizes and threaded inserts. I generally recommend the metal ones for areas able to afford them as they are more effective to sanitize and can be reused.

There is an embroidery hoop around the outside of the assembly, this is to attach a medical face mask to prevent dust from entering the airway after the tracheostomy. Try to clamp the mask just around the edges and allow it to billow in the middle a little as this will make exhaling easier for the horse. You can clamp it in place by stitching the two holes together to apply pressure on the hoop.


These devices are very serious pieces of equipment that are intended to be life saving devices. Please contact fuznuzhorseequipment@gmail.com before you attempt one of these prints for any additional guidance and support. These need to be printed and prepared well in advance of an emergency and stored and maintained properly.

name: Small 3" adjustable vent hole

name: Large cat food can lid
description:
There are a lot of cat owners that feed their furbabies Fancy Feast or other small-canned food, but we have a few big girls, and they like their full-sized 5.5 oz (155 g) Authority cans.

The lid on this one is a bit thicker than most, and I really dislike the idea of opening the lid without a tab (might get cat food on your fingers, you know), so I added one of those.

I'm printing these with a delta printer and a Bowden extruder, and it's working oddly well.  Using Amazon's TPU in red at 230 degrees C, and the bed at 50 degrees of the same.  Takes about an hour and 45 to get it all done with 100% infill.  The text is our cattery name that I was about to put on the lid so we could make them for promotional items - this text isn't on the .stl file.

8.28.19: Adjusted the lid seal to be larger, and increased the overall diameter by 1mm to allow for a proper fit.
comments:
Just a note, I have found that these settings work REALLY WELL with TPU on an Ender 3, with Bowden Tube!!!
I use Simplify3D for my slicer.
My tip is 0.4mm and I undersize it in the settings to 0.35. I also do outline overlap of 25% and perimeter overlap of 25%.
-Extrusion multiplier = 1.20
-Auto Extrusion width
-NO RETRACTION ON BOWDEN TUBE FOR TPU!!!
-Layer height = 0.16 (conforms to the lift vs rotation steps factor - works quite perfectly!)
-number of outlines, shells, top and bottom layers = your choice, but account for usage durability!
-skirt or brim...your choice depending on how much surface contact your object has.
-Infill, your choice on percentage and type. I increase the extrusion width to 110%.
-Support, your discretion.
-Temperature, Extruder = 220C, Bed = 65C....use hairspray on a heated glass bed...different coefficient of expansion between glass and object allows extremely easy removal when all is cooled!!!
-Fan Cooling = None!, Except for Bridging which applied at 100%.
-Special G-Code Instructions, None.
-Special Scripts - None.
-Printing Speeds - Default=30mm/sec, Outline Underspeed=50%, Solid Infill Underspeed=80%, Support Structure Underspeed=80%, X/Y Axis Movement Speed=80mm/sec, Z Axis Movement Speed=16.7mm/sec.
Bridging Extrusion Multiplier=100% (I sometimes drop down to 90 or 80% if bridging sags too much due to the 1.20 extrusion multiplier.) ...Doesn't hurt to tinker with this percentage!!!
-Movement Behavior(Advanced Tab)-Avoid crossing outline for travel movements, Maximum allowed detour factor=20 ....I RARELY uncheck this!!! Reduces Stringing!!!

Infill: 12%
Print speed: 75 mm/sec
Support/Adhesion: none
Print time: 4hr 40min

UPDATE: I've added the files to build the modular handle. 
Cut your 1/2" PVC into two sections of desired length. 
Glue the connector halfway into the end of one PVC section.
Feed a length of 1/8" flat elastic through the connector, until it comes out the other end of the PVC.
Tie the elastic to an end cap, and place the end cap into the PVC pipe.
Slide the clip onto the other section of PVC pipe.
Feed the other end of the elastic through this section of PVC, pull it tight, tie it to the other end cap, and place the end cap into the PVC opening.

UPDATE: Introducing the Low Rider Slim, with a more oblong design, for better catches on smaller dogs.

name: Fish Feeder - self-contained eco system
description:
First of all this is NOT a traditional fish food feeder. It is a self-contained eco solution that flows like this:  fish food > booklice > fish

My fish food (flakes) tends to get moist in Singapore's humid weather, even with silica gel packs. That leads to booklice breeding in the thousands - but before you get squeamish, look it up. I used to throw out the food and get fresh packs only for this to reoccur before long. 

One day I fed my fishes some flakes WITH the booklice by mistake but to my surprise none died, in fact they loved it. Figuring this was a protein trade-up, I've been waiting for the li'l critters to crawl to the cap and (you guessed it) tap it to send them to a watery end.

Additionally I noticed they are so small they crawl out of a tightly sealed cap, so I started immersing the food bottle in a water dish. But I guess they don't understand water because everyday loads of them drown.

So, here is a simple holder that supports a small bottle of fish food (42.5mm dia) on the side of the tank (4.8mm glass) and the arm is submerged, so there is no way for the booklice to crawl out, except to feed the fishes automatically, as they feed on flake food.
comments: woaGenius!

name: 1-ZollStopfen
description:
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/8hDf8PKKIJM

Diese Stopfen dienen als Hilfsmittel für einen Überlauf nach dem Prinzip der Kommunizierenden Röhren. Man kann dies nutzen um ein Aquarium welches auf der gleichen Höhe wie ein weiteres steht, miteinander zu verbinden. Ich nutzte dies auch um ein Filterbecken zu verbinden.

Problem ist dabei das wenn man eine größere Wassermenge im Umlauf hat (durch Filterpumpen etc), auch größere Wassermengen transportieren muss, dazu sind größere Schlauchdurchmesser erforderlich. Um dieses System zu initiieren muss der Schlauch 100% mit Wasser gefüllt sein. Ich drucke also 2x diese Stopfen, verschließe eine Seite mit dem stopfen, und halte den Schlauch komplett unter Wasser. Denn drücke ich unter Wasser den zweiten Stopfen hinein und kann den Schlauch platzieren. Danach die Stopfen herausziehen und schauen ob der Überlauf funktioniert.

Ich habe den ersten Stopfen in ABS mit 15% infill gedruckt. Eine höhere Infill Rate wäre aber optimal, da sonst einiges an Stabilität verloren geht. Auch kann man jedes Material benutzen was sich in Wasser nicht auflöst.
Viel Spaß mit den Teilen.
comments:
In 50% gedruckt. Passt perfekt für 12x2mm Aquariumschlauch.

Printed in 50% . Fits perfect for 12mm hose

name: Protective screen for residential unit
description:
Защитный экран для жилого модуля.

Поселил свою маленькую колонию жнецов в формикарии от artGuard. Но королева моей колонии очень нервничает находясь на свету. Поэтому я разработал модель экрана для жилого модуля.

Прошу обратить внимание на то, что я использую жилой модуль нового типа (под предметное стекло), а также в качестве крепежа применяю винты м4х25 с головкой под шестигранник (головка винта выступает на 2,5мм).

Крепление экрана к жилому модулю осуществляется посредством двух магнитов (они расположены как раз напротив головок винтов). Некоторое время назад, я разобрал несколько своих старых внутриканальных наушников и извлек из них неодимовые магниты. Магниты круглые с диаметром 6,5мм и толщиной 1,5мм.

После распечатки модели, магниты плотно вставляются в углубления. Экран примагничивается к головкам винтов и располагается на расстоянии 1мм. от стекла, что практически к минимуму сводит проникновение света в жилой блок и не царапает стекло.

name: CO2-Reaktor
description: This thing is a CO2-Reactor for Aquarium. You can push up the ph-value. Switch on after 5min.the CO2-Reactorpump in the Reactor. After the ph is high enough stop the pump and the close the valve. I have used SM-038 600l/h from Amazon. The bottom cover i have glued with silikon on the housing. I have cut away the supporting material from the suck in chamber at half or you can take  the supporting material complete out and fill the chamber with little bio balls to fast mixing the sucked water with the CO2 gas. This is meant to be used for those who have arthritus in the hand. If you want to take your pet for a walk, it is a pain to move the latching mechanism on the leash. This snap fit apparatus should solve the problem!
comments: Perfect, thank you!The male end is clipped to a dog's leash. The dog end is clipped to the dogs collar ring. When you want to walk, the male end inserts into the dog end, rotates 90 degrees and "snaps" into place. Then you're good to go. When the walk is done, rotate the male end 90 degrees back to unsnap and remove. The dog end can stay on the dog's collar as a dog tag when not in use for walks. The customizer is in a cleanup process right now so that only text parameters can be changed. Give me a few days and I will post that edit. Does this answer your question?Please could you explain how this works? Thanks.

name: Bubble Blaster 3000 Skimmer Adapter For SRO XP 3000
description:
An adapter to get from the square bubble blaster volute cover, to the slip fitting in an Super Reef Octopus XP 3000 skimmer.

Background:

My trusty SRO XP3000 recently had a failure at the Bubble Blaster Pump after a good 5 years of service.  The volute cover broke, which required ordering a new one from CoralVue.


25 bucks, and 20 shipping later...

The new cover was a perfect match except where it connected to the skimmer.  The manufacturer had glued a metric threaded fitting on where the slip fitting should go.

This part adapts from the metric 50mm threads to the SRO slip fitting allowing the spendy replacement to be used.

Next up, printing a new volute cover!  So overpriced....

name: Autoaqua Smart ATO Tank Edge Bracket Holder
description:
Just a really simple bracket for the in-tank sensor for the AutoAqua Smart ATO system.

The little sensor does come with a small magnet, however it doesn't stop the sensor from tilting left/right meaning your water level readings will be off. Plus, the magnet is kinda weak anyway.

The sensor slides in from the front and hangs over the tank edge, holding the sensor itself securely in-place so it doesn't rotate or slide.

I have added the STL and the Fusion 360 file so you can edit the lip if you have thicker/thinner tank glass. Its currently set for 5.5mm glass.

Recommend that you print this in ABS, it will last longer than a PLA print, but in my experience, with constant contact with the water, the ABS part only lasts around 3-4 months before its very weak.

14/05/2020
Added a V2 version of the file which has a baffle at the front and twin hooks to allow the sensor to slide in from the rear. In the evening, my sensor was being hit with sunlight, "blinding" the sensor and causing it to empty my entire RO water container into the tank, not good. This will need supports if printing on an FDM machine.

If printing on a DLP/LCD resin based machine, get the V2_DLP file. This is pre-sliced with supports in all the right places to ensure a trouble free print. DO NOT put this resin printed part straight into you tank. You can coat the printed part in Krylon Fusion or Plastidip to seal it from the aquarium. Both of these coatings have been used with success by other reef keepers.

name: PetSafe Healthy Pet Simply Feed conveyor belt trimming jig
description:
The smallest amount of food that can be dispensed with the PetSafe Healthy Pet Simply Feed automatic feeder is 1/8 cup which is too much for our purposes. I decided that shortening the "paddles" of the conveyor belt would be the easiest way to adjust the amount of food dispensed. With the belt removed from the conveyor assembly, this jig is placed around each paddle and a knife/blade is used to cut off the top (exposed) part of the paddle to shorten it. The paddles are originally 18mm tall and this jig starts at 15mm tall. Using z-axis scaling, I incrementally reduced the height of the paddles, first to 15mm, then 12mm, then 10mm, and ending with 8mm tall paddles. I performed the following steps at each paddle height to calculate the amount of food dispensed: * Trim each paddle on the conveyor belt * Reassemble the conveyor, making sure to align a paddle with the alignment arrows located on the side of the conveyor near the top. This ensures the cavity fully dispenses when the conveyor stops * Put the conveyor back in the feeder, making sure a paddle is still aligned with the arrows. Ensure red lever is latched * Put the hopper back on top. Make sure the agitator lever is placed inside the hole of the hopper) * Fill hopper part way with food * Using navigation buttons on feeder, do "prepare conveyor with food" (enter + left) * After conveyor has been prepared with food, empty any dispensed food back into hopper * With food bowl empty, do "prepare conveyor with food" again * When that is completed, weight the dispensed food and divide by 8 (since a "prepare" cycle empties 8 sections of food). I would place the filled food bowl on my kitchen scale, zero the scale, dump the food back into the hopper, then place the empty food bowl back on the scale which would show the food weight. * Repeat the last two steps 4-6 times and average the results to get the average food dispensed in each section. 
    Paddle height        Food dispensed
    18 mm (original)     14.5 grams
    15 mm                12.0 grams
    12 mm                 9.3 grams
    10 mm                 6.6 grams
     8 mm                 4.2 grams (29% of original amount)
I chose the 8mm paddle height which resulted in a little less than one-third of the original food dispensed. I strongly suggest slowly reducing the paddle height and measuring the amount of food dispensed at each height. I think the varying sizes and shapes of kibble will result in different amounts dispensed than I calculated with my cat's food. After choosing the 8mm paddle height I had to reconfigure the meal sizes with the navigation buttons. Since one section now dispenses about one-third of original, I would need to increase each meal size from 1/8 cup to 3/8 cup to maintain the same amount of food dispensed. Since our cat is a couple pounds overweight I only increased each meal size to 1/4 cup. Unfortunately I didn't take any pictures before I filled the whole hopper with food. I'll try to take some next time it's convenient.

name: Roof Brace for Feral Cat Shelter
description:
I bought this cat shelter for our outdoor cat:

https://www.amazon.com/ROCKEVER-Shelter-Outdoor-Rainproof-Three-Four/dp/B07S6PKN8R/?th=1

According to the assembly instructions, the roof is attached to the shelter with four screws, which means the only access to the interior is through the two entrances or, if the floors are removed, through the bottom. It's much more convenient to access the interior by removing the roof, but the ridge of the roof is rather flimsy, and taking the roof on and off will almost certainly break it eventually. I designed this brace to stiffen the roof and allow it to be removed to access the inside of the shelter without risking breakage. Note that there are alignment tabs on the roof which need to be positioned correctly when replacing the roof.

name: Cat Toy for straws
description:

The one which is uploaded is the third version shown in the last image. It uses less plastic and the center piece won't turn over making the hole inaccessible. 

Bend the straw as shown in the image before putting it in the toy and cats will have a hard time getting it out. It can still be removed with a little bit of force without damaging the print in my experience. 

You can also stick something like a stuffed animal on a stick in it as well. the dollar general in my area has some cheap ones that work as shown in the last image. 

I recommend printing the last 5-10 mm with solid infill using a height range modifier so that the toy will have a lower center of gravity and bounce back a bit. I found it necessary to slow down the printer for the first 3-4 layers when switching from 15 to 100% infill.

name: Chicken nipple guard / clamp
description:
Chicken nipple guard / clamp

Having purchased some stainless steel chicken nipples as an automatic watering solution, I thought my job was done. That is until my birds routinely started knocking the internal components out from the nipples / gravity valves, causing their water source to leak everywhere. What is worse is that I had installed two of the ten nipples I purchased in a 1.5" ABS pipe and the internal components were helplessly cemented inside the pipe! 3D printing to the rescue! Here is a design that clasps on to the rear of the stainless steel chicken nipples that I purchased, preventing the internals from being pecked out and draining the water supply. FreeCAD (design parameters) spreadsheet setup:
  • User defined dimensions are highlighted with red.
  • Computed values are marked in cyan.
  • All values can be edited.
The design was done in FreeCAD and as mentioned it is fully parametric. I have included the FreeCAD file so that you can modify the design to your heart's content. I am open to any suggestions as to how to improve the design work-flow in FreeCAD.

name: Float Switch Standoff 1.25 Inch
description:
I needed a standoff to insert a float switch into my Reef Octopus 200-INT skimmer. This allows for clearance from the lid so that once the skimmmate reaches just below the max level, the skimmer shuts off using my controller and I get an alert. There is a pre-threaded design and a non-threaded design that can be tapped on both sides (M8-1.25). 

Installation instructions:

-Drill appropriately sized hole. I had to drill an offset hole from one of the air vents to clear the side of the skimmer cup. 

-Remove nut and washer from float switch

-Thread cable through center

-Thread on standoff (male float thread to female standoff threads). Place the washer on the standoff male threads.

-Insert float switch cable and standoff into skimmer top and lock in place with nut. Do not overtighten!

name: Napfdeckel (Feeding Bowl Cap)
description:
Ihr kennt das sicherlich: Ihr füttert Eure Stubentiger und dann bleibt die Hälfte im Napf übrig, während die Kleinen im Garten toben oder ihr Revier durchforsten. Bislang haben wir uns immer mit Tupper-Dosen beholfen, doch sind die sehr klobig und nehmen viel Platz weg. Ein Deckel wäre super? Gedacht: Gedruckt. 

Ich habe diesen Deckel aus TPU gedruckt, da das Material sehr flexibel, ungiftig und somit unbedenklich für die Tierchen ist. Dabei ist das Ganze auch noch stabelbar: Hurra! 

Der Deckel ist für das Modell von Trixie (Durchmesser 15cm) gemacht. Da die Napfgrößen aber variieren, solltet Ihr den Napf vorher einmal messen und in Cura (oder dem Slicer Eurer Wahl) das Modell auf die gewünschte Größe bringen. Für unsere Näpfe passt das Modell in den Größen von 153-158mm. 

Vermutlich ist der Deckel auch für andere Anwendungszwecke zu gebrauchen. 

-- english version -- 

If you own cats you might have already experienced the situation: You feed your little tigers and then half of the food remains in the bowl while the cats are jumping through the garden or scour their territory. Until now we used tupper boxes, but as they are very bulky, they also take up a lot of space. A lid would be great? Thought: Printed.

I printed this lid out of TPU because the material is very flexible, non-toxic and therefore harmless to the animals. The whole thing is also still stable: Hooray!

The lid is made for the Trixie model (diameter 15cm). However, since the bowl sizes vary, you should measure the bowl beforehand and bring the model to the desired size in Cura (or the slicer of your choice). The model fits our bowls in sizes from 153-158mm.

It will also serve other use cases: Just scale it to your needs.

The bowl it's designed to work with is the one in the link, but step versions of the files are included to ease adapting it to others.

https://www.target.com/p/matte-stainless-steel-cat-38-dog-dish-bowl-silver-13-2oz-boots-38-barkley-8482/-/A-52263495#lnk=sametab

Printing:

Infill 7%, support may be needed for cut out for locking mechanism.

name: Bird Cage Pi Zero Case
description:
Here's a case for a Pi Zero to fill a VERY specific need. We have a little hedgehog, and I use the amazing PiKrellCam package on a Pi Zero to keep an eye on her with an IR-enabled camera board. This lets us monitor her habits and whether any issues come up overnight, since she's nocturnal (and don't worry, we also check on her constantly during the day in person, this just keeps an eye out for us while we're sleeping).

The Pi sandwiches in between the two case layers with a few M2.5 bolts, and is designed to zip-tie to the inside of the cage bars underneath the camera board, which sits in a separate printed enclosure. Since our Quaker Parrot likes to hang out on top of the hedgehog enclosure, all of the vents and other openings are protected from falling seed husks, poo, etc.

Note: At one time I had to remove the files and post a warning that the parts didn't fit properly. That issue has now been resolved, and these exact files printed and fit perfectly for me.

Wir haben für unsere Treppen im Haus diese Treppenschutzgitter von Safety 1st geholt. (es gehen bestimmt auch andere Treppenschutzgitter zum klemmen)
Da unsere Katze da aber nicht drüber springen möchte um an ihr Katzenklo im Keller zu kommen und alle Kinderschutzgitter mit Katzenklappe nicht Babysicher sein sollen, habe ich ein Abstandshalter zu beiden Seiten Designed.
Dadurch entsteht ein Spalt von 10cm (variabel einstellbar durch das Gitter selbst) und die Katze kann bequem vorbei. Mein Sohn passt mit seinem dicken Schädel da nicht durch ;) 
Bitte entsprechend auf den Kopfumfang des Kindes achten, wenn Ihr das nachdruckt. Ich übernehme keine Garantie!

Das Gitter sitzt auf jeden Fall sehr fest, man kann sich gegen lehnen und hat bereits das erste Jahr ohne Wackeln und bewegen überstanden.

Den Holzbalken könnte man auch weglassen und direkt an der Treppe befestigen, aber dann wär die Lücke entsprechend größer gewesen. Unsere Treppenbreite ist mit 91cm ziemlich breit.

Ich kann bei Bedarf auch gern die Original Datei bereitstellen, wenn ihr das anpassen wollt.


Das ist das verwendete Treppenschutzgitter: https://www.amazon.de/Safety-1st-Treppenschutzgitter-sicheres-Metall-T%C3%BCrschutzgitter/dp/B01G4WERBU?keywords=kindergitter+safety+1st&qid=1656616903&sprefix=kindergitter+saft%2Caps%2C73&sr=8-5&linkCode=ll1&tag=fruitjes0d-21&linkId=1014906befa19404ddcb2f7adb2adbf5&language=de_DE&ref_=as_li_ss_tl

Wenn du auf so einen Verweislink klickst und über diesen Link einkaufst, bekomme ich von deinem Einkauf eine Provision. Für dich verändert sich der Preis nicht.*

name: Luftheber / Wasserpumpe / Skimmer / Airlift
description:
Luftheber / Wasserpumpe / Skimmer / Airlift 
(English see below)

Der Luftheber saugt Wasser aus dem langen Kamin und stößt es durch den kurzen Stummel aus. Hier kann ein Schlauch angebracht werden, dann kann eine nennenswerte Menge Wasser einige 10cm höher als die Wasseroberfläche gefördert werden. Je tiefer der Luftheber unter der Wasseroberfläche angebracht ist, desto mehr und höher wird Wasser gefördert. 

In dem langen Kamin wird ein Skimmer (z. B. siehe https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5164329 ) angebracht.

Da keine mechanische Pumpe das Wasser verwirbelt, ist die Pumpe ungefährlich für Kleinlebewesen (z.B. Garnelen)

Benötigt wird (min. eine) Luftpumpe für den Luftstrom. Den zweiten Luftadapter ggfs. verschließen.


Airlift / Water pump / Skimmer 


The air-lift sucks water out of the long chimney and expels it through the short stub. A hose can be attached here, then a considerable amount of water can be pumped a few 10cm higher than the water surface. The deeper the airlift is placed below the water surface, the more and higher the water is pumped. 

A skimmer (e.g. see https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5164329 ) is installed in the long chimney.

Since there is no mechanical pump swirling the water, the pump is not dangerous for small creatures (e.g. shrimps).

You need (at least one) air pump for the air flow. Close the second air adapter if necessary.

name: Large Running Disc Cage Bracket
description:
I read that running wheels aren't good for rats, causing them to need to arch their backs (tail included) backwards, and run in an un-natural in-ratly (I made that term up) position, and there is apparently no COTS solution for a cage mounted running disc.
The mass of the base for the running disc, I have, didn't seem stable enough for the mass of an adult rat to be able to continuously run without sliding all over the place and then to be obstructed by the cage walls or some other obstruction.
I also didn't like the floor space the non-cage-mounted solution took up; So this can be more strategically mounted just off the edge of a shelf, leaving plenty of playroom everywhere else.

Everything I do will also always be a "work in progress".  I didn't put any holes for mounting. I drilled holes and epoxied M4 screw heads to act as studs, with larger 3D printed makeshift nuts to capture two horizontal cage bars per stud.

I printed at 10% infill (to save filament), with 3 vertical shell perimeters (for stronger 
vertical surfaces).  I spray painted with hammer beaten something to dissolve the surface plastic and to bond with the paint; making external layers a more continuous stronger substance.

name: Cat Pilling Aid
description:
Autumn and I mastered many things together as she grew older, but pills was not one.  Many oral medicines were ok, even sub-cutaneous fluids, but pills were always difficult.  We tried many aids and what I found didn't work for us.   After she passed, I decided I shoudl try 3D printing what I think would have helped.

It is designed to work as an adaptor on a 1ml oral medication syringe.  Autumn and I had plenty of these from the vet for other oral medications.

I printed in PETG for food safety.     After printing,  make sure to file or sand to remove the rough parts around the supports where would come in contact with kittie's mouth.  Trim any stray fiber to avoid potential ingestion as well.

The syringe should fit snugly.   The pin slides into the syringe so the pin will poke out the end when depressed. 

I use the second and third fingers on the handles, and thumb on the plunger.  As you push the plunger, the pin helps dislodge the pill, and the forward pressure releases the arms.

There are nubs on the arms that allow applying a rubber band to add additional pressure.
comments: God bless you! I have a 18yo cat and it's extremelly difficult giving her medicine. Hopefully this will help!

name: Wavemaker Guard/Anemone Guard for Vesta Wave Slim and other small wavemakers
description:
After losing an anemone to my wavemaker, I went looking for a solution, but couldn't find one, so I made my own! Here's my attempt at a wavemaker cover! There's two versions one is open at the top and a full cage. 

The open one should work just fine for protecting anemones, as the intake of the wavemaker is covered. But since the top is left open, it won't impact the water flow or speed. If an anemone decides to stroll past, at worst, it should get stuck to the guard instead of getting sucked into the impeller, However since it's open, it probably can't stop an anemone that's determined to get inside, but I figure the vibrations, strong water flow and noise should be enough to dissuade it. There's a full cage version, but I don't really recommend it, as it DRAMATICALLY cuts down on the flow speed and also redirects the flow.

I'm using a Vesta Wave Slim, but it should work for you if your wavemaker is around 35mm in diameter.

name: Articulating 40x10mm Through Glass Fan Mount for Vivarium/Terrarium
description:
Design: 
I designed this fan to go through a 5/8" hole drilled in glass, so that I could position the fan within the inside of the tank accurately. The glass thickness I designed for is 3/16", but it should work for most thicknesses. 

Fit:
The ball-joints are snap fit, and the assembly is held together using the stainless steel mesh between the fan inner and outer housings. The roughness of the printed surfaces definitely will impact the 'tightness' of the ball joints. The fit may be too loose with high accuracy prints, so a little inaccuracy is okay. Also, the more the internal joints are moved the looser the fit becomes, so keep that in mind. 

Notes: 
I used 40 mesh size stainless steel mesh. 
I used a dupont 2-pin connector, which fits nicely through the hole in the articulating fan arm

Printing: 
I used a 0.6mm nozzle, with anywhere from 0.2 to 0.4mm layer height. 

Parts: 
1: Fan Nut
2: Threaded Ball Joint Connector
3: Ball Joint Connector Extension
4: Fan Housing Inner
5: Fan Housing Outer

I also made a smaller mount that you can screw the silencer into, instead of in the skimmer cup, to keep the height above the aquarium down and give you space for extra tubing on the input for further reduced noise. #Erste eigene Veröffentlichung
Ein kleines "Trinkglas" Aquarium.

Angesteuert wird das ganze mit einem Arduino Nano und der Lib. FASTLED
Der Code für die Wellensimulation folgt noch. 
Man brauch noch Messing oder Aluminiumstangen aus dem Baumarkt.
In diesem Falle 6mm Messingrohr.(1m kostet ca. 3 €)
Länge der 3 Rohre müssen angepasst werden.

Oh und bitte beachten, das ist auf keinem Fall für Fische geeignet.
Grünzeug,Boden,Würmer und Flohkrebse aus dem Bach nebenan.

# First own publication
A small "drinking glass" aquarium.
For illumination, I use the WS2812B LEDs.(Thangs to crilitech)
The whole thing is controlled with an Arduino Nano and the Lib. FASTLED
The code for the wave simulation follows.
You still need brass or aluminum rods from the hardware store.
In this case 6mm brass tube. (1m costs about 3 €)
Length of the 3 tubes must be adjusted.

Oh and please note, this is by no means suitable for fish.
Green stuff, soil, worms and flea crabs from the creek next door.

name: Aquarium Light Rack
description:
# Aquarium Light Fixture Bracket / Raiser
A visually pleasing way to raise your light bar off the top of the tank

### Features 
- Raise light bar ~7cm above the tank for optimal coverage of aquarium and floating plants
- Adjustable glass width with a simple screw-in design
- Easy 3 piece print per side with simple angles and no overhangs
- Two different bolt styles (heart and circle heads)
- 6.7mm opening with a 4mm guard to make sure the light doesn't fall in during cleaning or accidental bumps
- Subdued and stylish design to not take away from the beauty of the tank

### My use case
I have a rimless aquarium and floating plants. I just bought a Fluval 3.0 light fixture and love it other than its mounting options. It sits too low and I wanted it to cover my tank more evenly. 

This fits a standard Fluval 3.0 light fixture (I think all sizes) It fits super well on my rimless tank.

### Disclaimer
I do not recommend tightening the bolt until it is compressing the glass. Eventually the bolt head will pop off and if you don't use PLA or PETG you can harm the aquarium if it falls in. Just tighten until flush and it will stay perfectly :).

### Example
Black & Clear:
- PETG backplate
- UV Clear Resin Bolt

### Printer
Currently I'm running an Ender 3 v2 with 0 modification. I also have a Photon Mono 4K that I used for the bolts, but they're pretty simple, I think the ender could've printed the bolts just fine.

name: Chick toe straightener
description:
Every once in awhile, a chick hatches with curled toes. the current standard method is to use tape and/or carboard to help flatten the toes, but that only works vertically, and toes can still end up twisted horizontally. This implement is just wide enough for the toes, making sure they stand upright, just as a taco holder would cradle a delicious corn flour hammock of tasty... i digress.. 

To use it, first tape the bottom up with something quite sticky, I used a cloth plaster. then slip the chick's feet and toes into the grooves, making sure they aren't curled, of course. finish up by taping over the top as well to effectively sandwich those toes in there. try not to tape up the ankle as well otherwise it wont be able to stand/walk/hobble around. when removing, the top should come off easily, if the bottom does, a dab of cooking oil will help release the plastic. congrats! your chick is now a duckling. 

turn your duckling back into a chick (by removing the printed part) every 24 hours or so, and check to see if the toes are straight. if they are, you've ensure a happy life of scratching in the dirt for the fluff ball. go get yourself some cookies. if not, keep trying for a couple more days. It fixed 2 of my chicks in just 20 hours each, so one day should be good enough. 

I modeled it to fit a full-sized breed. if you have bantams, or bigger birds you can scale it to match. just scale the line width as well (its meant to be printed in 0.5mm lines, so if you print at 80%, used 0.4mm lines). the rest of the print settings are up to you, please be carfeul to remove any blobs or strings so the chick doesnt get chaffed feet.

name: acrylic ant formicarium inspired by AC Omni Nest (small)
description:
An acrylic nest inspired by ants Canada's small omni nest. Laser cut acrylic plates and connect the parts with 6mm bolts. The bolts should be at least 30mm if not longer. 
the first 3 files are .ai and contain all of the types of parts ready to laser cut.
the next 3 are .stl and contain a cover to block light, a replacement 5mm part called "gate" used for the entrance and a structure for holding metal grids in place.
The rest are the raw vector files for all of the individual parts, the thickness and the amount you have to cut in case you want those.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Most of the parts are 3mm thick while some 5mm. If you don't have any 5mm plates you can use 4 or 6mm. Just remember to 3d print the part "gate" since it can't be any other size.
The entrance is 10mm wide to fit transparent pvc tubes just like the original.
The square compartment is for the humidifying sponge or cotton whatever you choose. 
It is recommended to place a small metal grid where the sponge connects to the nest to prevent the ants from digging out. If the metal grid slides away you can print the part called "grid holder" to keep it in place.


I've included an extra piece with a hole for a drinking sponge if you want more of those directly inside the rooms. There is an adaptor for a 14mm test tube you can fill up with water to supply the colony for months.

name: Litter Genie Square to Round Refill Adapter
description:
Note: I first uploaded this to Printables (https://www.printables.com/model/406270-litter-genie-square-to-round-refill-adapter), just posting here too. I created this adapter for my Litter Genie (pail to put dirty cat litter in) in order to use round refills instead of the proprietary square refills. The only square refills I found available to purchase are the name brand, which are expensive and don't last long. The round refills are a common shape used by other products like the Litter Locker, Diaper Genie, etc and much cheaper generic brands are available that last longer. Amazon has their own brand of them, Target has one, among others. This adapter should work with any round refill meant for Diaper Genie (or similar) products. I've been buying the Amazon brand (mama bear) since they are a good price and you get a discount with subscribe and save. This is the very first thing I designed and created on my own, and was a fun project to learn Fusion 360 on. It took me a while to get the measurements and everything right, and lots of test prints, but I'm pretty happy with how it turned out. Figured I'd share it in case anyone else who has a Litter Genie would like to give it a try and save some money on refills.

How to Use

Take a round refill and pull out some of the bag and tie it off (same way you would normally start your square refill). Insert the round refill into the adapter. Its a tight fit - I added nubs on the front and sides of the adapter that purposely presses the round refill a bit, which creates a necessary gap that the lid of the Litter Genie needs to fit into. I included some pictures to show what I mean. Ensure the round refill is fully seated into the adapter. The adapter should slide right into the Litter Genie where you would normally insert the square refill. Make sure to orient the adapter the correct way - I added text to indicate the Front of the adapter. This is so the 3 nubs are in the correct position (no nub in the back). The lid should close properly, and fit into the front and side gaps between the refill and adapter.

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B09YBV6PZP

Unfortunately they neglected to mention in the product description that they only provided a latch for opening the gate in a single direction, which was the opposite of the direction I wanted.

Rather than disassemble the gate and send it back, I designed my own latch based on the original one and made a mirror in my slicer. I also beefed it up quite a bit in case the 3d print was any weaker (note we're using this for a dog, not a baby... I wouldn't recommending printing baby gate parts).

Note this requires a small screw, washer and spring that came with the original latch. I'm not 100% sure of the size of each. The spring has about a 5mm OD and it's maybe 20mm long.

name: Humane Mouse Trap (remix)
description:
Исходный вариант мышеловки никак не хотел срабатывать (мелкие мыши), пришлось на торец корпуса закрепить гайку M8, чтобы срабатывала от более легкого веса.
Поэтому пришлось внести несколько изменений в исходные модели.

1) Добавил решётку в торцевой стенке корпуса - стало удобнее крепить приманку.
2) На 6 мм удлинил часть корпуса, в которой крепится приманка - мышеловка стала более чувствительной. 
3) На дверь и на корпус добавил места под магниты 5х5х1,75 мм. для четкого и надежного закрывания дверцы при срабатывании ловушки.
4) Добавил решётку и на дверцу тоже и немного изменил форму упоров.

name: medium outworld for ant farm
description:
A 7*12cm outworld with 10mm holes. the roof and sides are 3mm laser cut acrylic.
Can be used to feed medium ant colonies. Connect this to the formicarium with 10mm plastic tubes. The main plastic frame does require support but comes out wonderfully using tree supports.

The top of the roof has two options, either you use the piece with big holes and glue a mesh in between the two acrylic plates. If you don't want to do that there is also a piece with ventilation holes cut in, however some small ant species are able to escape through there (this piece also has to be glued together with the other roof plate).
If you want to escape proof your outworld there is also an alternative piece for the roof where the lower plate is in two separate pieces, so the outer part can get anti climbing stuff on and stay attached to the main frame.

Ive included a small feeding plate so you can more easily put food into the outworld without contaminating the floor or sediment. There is also an adaptor for 14mm glass test tubes found in the supermarket.

name: Bird feeder
description:
A simple bird feeder to provide either peanuts or fat balls to garden birds.

The feeder consists of four 3D printed parts, as shown in the pictures. Printing the parts with 15% infill works well. To connect the parts, I used welding rods that can be cheaply obtained from almost any hardware shop. The welding rods are available in 1.6 or 2.0 mm diameter, so I made two sets of models. The welding rods can be easily cut to size by using cutting pliers or a hacksaw.

The models have room for 24 rods, which works well for peanuts. By placing fewer rods (for example 8), the feeder can be used with fat balls instead of peanuts.

name: Table leg clamp
description: We bought two side tables for use with our recliners the idea being that their would be one for myself and one for my wife.  Unfortunately we didn't have enough space to place two tables and two recliners side-by-side so we ended up putting two tables together.  Now we have a house cat (who is no light weight) that loves to jump on tables.  It doesn't take much weight in the wrong place to tip over a table with three legs.  Since we hat the tables together where two legs of one table were right next to two legs of the other table I decided to come up with a clamp to connect the legs together giving us a single table with six legs which is much more stable.  I used four clamps, two on the bottom and two on the top and now the cat can jump on the table to his hearts desire and still not tip it over - of course that still doesn't prevent him from knocking everything off the table but it's a start.
instruction: Priint out four copies of the clamp and place two low and two high.

name: Cat and Dog Food Divider for 800g Tin Cans
description:
Conventional pet food gadgets only divide the food within the tin can. In high cans it is a big problem then to get the first portion out of the can.
The dispenser provided here enables it to divide the wished amount of food and take it out of the can afterwards.  

Usage: Set the divider centric on top of the opened tin can and press it down until it sits on the foods surface.
Then rotate it clockwise and a stripe of food will be cutted out and shifted upwards trough the gap. A whole revolution dispenses 100g of food. If you need 150g, for example, make one and a half revolutions.
Now you can lift the divider together with the food and empty it into the feeding dish.

Try to hold the divider always at a constant height and do not apply downforce. Otherwise the remaining food underneath the divider will be squeezed and the blade will haul too much food. If you need more than 100g make one revolution at first at constant height. Then press the divider down like at start until it touches the food surface again. Now you can continue the rotation. 

This model is just under development. I would be glad to get feed back and suggestions for its improvement.

name: Modular formarium
description:
What we have:
- a modular form, in which you can easily block the moves, change and add sections.
- Keeps moisture well despite small size.
- effectively uses space.
- Extremely easy to manufacture (if you have access to the printer).
- looks aesthetically.

Materials - PLA plastic, 90 mm lid from the petri dish, gypsum. The weight of plastic is 60 grams per section, it is printed for 5 hours.
We take the workpiece, prepare the gypsum - 90 grams of gypsum and 60 ml of water, fill it, close it, shake it well enough to cover the walls evenly, put it on the table, remove the lid, wash it, put it in place, remove it in an hour, dry it, connect, put the door, lock where necessary, fasten.

While I have connected 2 sections, I will expand, in due course I will replace the entire old formarium. Over time, I'll work on a more beautiful facade finish.

name: Dog Anti-Flea tracker/holder
description:
This is a simple holder for Vectra Anti-Flea tubes, to easily keep track if you've protected your dog this month yet.
You can easily apply it to the wall with double sided tape.
Since it's impractical to buy 12 tubes at once, there's a pin for each month, once you've used the tube, you can place the pin in the front position to remember/indicate that you've done so.
I also use the Seresto collar for summer months, so I added another row of holes and 2 arrow pins so I can remember when I opened the collar and to mark it's expiration month.
Also, there are two arrow designs: "Pino_2.5" is easier to print, flat on the bed.

In the future, I intend to add a cover for the bottom part of the tubes, since I placed this in the entrance hall and it's not the most esthetic piece of art.

Please see screenshot of Print Preview you will need to print on its edge to maximize strength do to printing layers orientation. 
Show me your prints if you do print this thank you.

name: Dog Door Screen Door Seal Brackets
description:
We hada problem with the dog door that we installed alongside our sliding door - there was no place for the screen door to seal against, so we could either close the screen door all the way (in which case the dog could not get in/out), or we could leave the screen door not closed all the way, which left a huge gap for bugs to get in.

Enter this very custom couple of brackets that mount to the top and bottom of our sliding door frame, to hold a 1x4 piece of wood for the screen door to close and seal against.

In order to make printing easier, I split both brackets into two pieces so that they can be printed without supports.

I never did get around to making a screw hole in the bottom bracket like I did for the top bracket, because I did not realize that the brackets needed this until I had already printed out the bottom bracket, and manually drilled a pilot hole for the screw.

I have included the Fusion 360 file in case someone decides to use this, although chances seem small that anyone will be able to use this directly unless they have a sliding door frame exactly like mine, and a dog door exactly like mine!

name: PetSafe Pet Feeder Paw Block
description:
I got a PetSafe feeder so I didn't have to wake up in the morning to feed my cat but she had other plans. She figured out how to stick her paw in the feeder slot and force more kibble out. Aside from making an awful racket while I try to sleep, I was worried she would injury a joint(have seen it before with another cat and another feeder).


This is a very quick and very dirty design using Dem0s's PetSafe Pet Feeder Adapter 's feeder interface as a base. Could use a bit of tweeking depending on your need but this works for me.

I printed this sitting upright and took it straight from the printer to the feeder and it stuck it in with a friction fit. Cat tested it and the friction fit seems to be holding up to her.
comments: Without wifi, I dont know if there is any difference in the opening though.Does this fit the petsafe feeder with or without wifi? Thanks.

name: Insect-A-Way Insect Live Saver
description:
We are currently witnessing the sixth meass-extinction event of earth history. Since the 1990s, we've had a decline in insect numbers of up to 80 percent, as a consequence, bird populations are collapsing as well. Do your part to help saving our environment. Stop killing insects just because they are in your apartment or house! We need every single one of them.

Print out this little device and put it onto your vacuum cleaner. Then, suck in the insect and close the lid on it. The insect will be trapped inside the device and you can easily carry it outside and release it into the freedom of nature. Every single insect saved can produce generations of children, helping to rebuild the dying insect populations. 

In case you don't have an own printer, you can obtain one Insect-A-Way printed by myself. Just drop me a line. Please don't sell the design nor the printed things. If you found this useful, please donate what you think it is worth to my paypal.me. Help cover the time of design.
Thanks, Enjoy!

name: Silent Spinner mount
description:
This is an extender mount for the Kaytee Silent Spinner. It moves the wheel away from the bars by about 2cm.

In our hamster's cage, it was not possible to use the standard bar mount due to the fact that the wheel would then rub against the sidewalls of the lower half of the cage. The included metal feet are nice on a solid surface, but useless if you give your hamster any decent amount of bedding to burrow. I had to clear the wheel every day from the surrounding bedding to allow the hamster to run during the night.

This mount plugs into the existing mount just like the metal feet do. This was designed for a 6.5" Silent Spinner, and was not tested on any other wheel. It is also designed for a dwarf hamster, so this doesn't necessarily need to be extremely strong.

name: Mesh cover for dog wound 1
description: Protect my dog's open, inoperable, wound (approx 2" dia) from being licked, while keeping the wound exposed to the air to allow it to scab over. Center "web" or "mesh" goes over the wound, with the "paddles" (side pieces) keeping the web just above the wound (note how the inner edges of the two paddles on top of the web are slightly higher; that's the side that goes against the wound, so that only the paddles make contact with the wound), which should make it more comfortable for the dog. Bandage wraps go around the "paddles" and may cross over the web/mesh, but, the more open the web area is, the better. I secure the bandages with medical sticky wrap, but, medical tape or similar will do (avoid anything sharp, such as the pointy pieces of metal that attach to some injury wraps).

name: Mexican Jumping Beans - Watering/Storage Solution
description:
Mexican Jumping Beans - Watering/Storage Solution
----------------------------------------------------------

**DESIGNED TO FIT ON SLA PRINTERS**
**PRINTS SUPPORT/RAFT FREE**

How to Use (Watering Station)
----------------
1.  Print base and shelf
2.  Insert shelf into base, should rest on edge of base
3.  Get a plate, place a paper towel down
4.  Set base w/ shelf on plate with paper towel
5.  Cut paper towel to fit inside base w/ shelf
6.  Put paper towel (2 layers) onto shelf
7.  Place Mexican Jumping Beans onto paper towel on shelf
8.  Sprinkle distilled/pure water over beans until mildly saturated
9.  Allow to soak for 10 minutes to 3 hours
10.  Dry off beans and place back into safety enclosure

How to Use (Storage)
----------------
1. Clean off water from base and shelf
2. Store beans with a dry paper towel, optionally store in the plastic case it came with

name: Little Friends Landmark Animal Cage Replacement Hamster Wheel Spindle
description:
Modified to fit the [Little Friends Landmark Animal Cage](https://www.amazon.co.uk/Little-Friends-Landmark-Animal-Accessories/dp/B00OFPLTA6/ref=dp_prsubs_1?pd_rd_i=B00OFPLTA6&psc=1) bars spacing and wheel spindle length/thickness.

After printing my own, I recommend printing on its side and using supports, the STL loads in this orientation by default.
This will print the spindle with the filament strands running along the entire length of the spindle, so the sheering force will then be distributed along the entire 30mm spindle.  

Printing it with the spindle pointing upwards, means the sheering force is concentrated on an area only 4mm wide and will break easily when the spindle tip is compressed to fit the wheel onto the spindle.

I wasted my filament, so you don't have to!

Pro tip: Add a drop of sunflower or olive oil to the spindle before fitting, and it will spin silently and be safe for the Hamster.

Print Settings:
Quality: 0.2
Infill: 40-60%
Brim: Yes (Personal Preference)
Supports: No
Material: PLA
comments: Hamsters are burrowing creatures and they are nocturnal. Please do not use these tiny cages, as they have no room to create burrows. It's like a tiny hamster hell. Please look into making a DIY enclosure from a medium/large storage bin; it only costs a few dollars. It gives them some small respite from the light and allows them to express their instincts. They are not domesticated and will go crazy in a tiny cage.

name: Klir Di-4 Adapter Plate Red Sea Reefer 250 V3 Sump
description:
I spent many hours mocking this up many different ways in Tinkercad. I spent over 100 hours printing many test versions. I sold one on Ebay that really impressed the buyer who has used it for 6 months now but not much interest there so here it is for free. It is a very tight drop in fit. I use aquarium sealant to close gaps basically anywhere water touches. I ran my last model for 9 months and 3 rolls of fleece. This is my latest design.  

Working great! In order to work great your sump water level needs to cover the bottom half of the Klir otherwise dirty water tends to bypass the fleece where it isn't submerged. Once I raised the water it worked better than ever and very quiet. I had to raise my skimmer though.


Print time with Prusa slicer.... 20 hours. Sure it could be made thinner etc. but I wanted a solid piece of kit!

name: Feeder saver for Ferplast Brava 6 birdfeeder
description: History: I needed something to prevent my Java Sparrow to spill their seeds everywhere in the aviary. So based on the dimensions of the Ferplast Brava 6 birdfeeder, i made this “saver” we all can see on other brands and other birdfeeders. It seems to work well enough :-). They don't jump in the seeds anymore, or less than previously. So i decided to share it with you. Simple print for a simple object but useful. Two longitudinal reinforcements end up stiffening the protection. Print instructions: Printed in petg (transparent for me) Sunlu brand - 230°C hotend / 90°C bed 0.4mm nozzle Layer 0.3mm 3 perimeters combine infill every 2 layers Infill 50%. No supports. Printed with Mk3s+ on textured sheet. You can print it on it's back, like the stl model. Addendum: PS: The “holes” may not be perfectly centered or aligned. Feel free to remodel for your own usage if you like it. PPS: I prefer the PETG for this usage as PLA is more like a sugar i didn't want my birds to “eat” this support. PPPS: This is my thing already on my Prusaprinters account.

name: Bird Feeder
description:
Bird feeder made to be mounted on a window glass with double sided adhesive tape or on a tree with nylon clamps. I used Don Deal double sided adhesive tape. It is strong enough to hold full filled feeder.
To assembly it you need a bottle with 62-63 mm of inner diameter and straight walls.
Two screws with nuts M2x6 (I used stainless steel) to fix a rain cover cap. And two screws M2x10 to fix a bottom part to a bottle. Last part you need is a stick (I used sushi stick with diameter about 5,4 mm).
I always print parts with lower hole diameter then I need and drill it out with drill bits.
You can print bottom part with 20% infill and mount part with 100%. I used PETG but it doesn't matter. Maybe ABS is not a good idea because it is not suitable for contact with food.
You can adjust seeds level in a feeding pool by cutting the edge of a bottle. If birds are to active or heavy weighted shakes of a feeder can cause seeds to spill out.
